<br>
Serious question:  How come there has not been a tradition of reporting strange SOUNDS around the loch?  Nessie is damned quiet, for a beastie. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/uyaish.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Yaish</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/29/02 5:27:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesmysteriouscreaturesfactorfiction.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What's Nessie?</span><hr size=1> Hiya Frater, LTNS<br>
<br>
Anyway, on to Ness.<br>
<br>
Loch Ness was formed roughly 10,000 years ago during the last glacial period.  At that time it was nothing more than a gouge in the earth filled with glacial ice.  As the ice melted and other factors filled the crevice the Loch was formed.<br>
Loch Ness is a land locked lake with only one outlet to the sea.  The surface of the loch is well above sealevel, not what one would expect were there undersea caverns that connected to the loch.  The only way for a creature from the sea to arrive at the loch is by the river ness, which runs right through the heart of downtown Inverness.<br>
On its way the river has several locks for boat travel, all of which are too small for a large creature to pass through unobserved.  Of the few ways up the river ness that bypass the locks all are extremely shallow (the reason for the locks)  In fact fishermen routinely wade across the knee deep river at several points.  At the top of the river at the entrance to the loch there is a stone weir that crosses the entire mouth.  This stone wall is only 18 inches below the surface of the water, and any creature entering from the sea would have to expose themselves as they crossed over.<br>
Some sea creatures do make it into the loch however.  Seals are frequent guests, though very rarely seen.  Several seals breaching the water in a row would look just like a series of humps, one of the most common nessie sightings.<br>
Loch Ness is also on Great Glenn fault, a fairly active seismic area.  Not surprisingly many of the nessie sighting happen shortly after small tremors, mostly unnoticed by the locals.  What the tremors do though is stir up sediments on the bottom, releasing trapped gasses, breaking free downed logs, and creating seiche waves, which the lochs geography is uniquely suited for.  Seiche waves are the main cause of the wakes that are seen but have no obvious source.<br>
<br>
The evidence just isnt there for nessie to be an actual creature, though there is ample evidence to explain the sightings. <p>The main problem with religions is that they think they are THE way, not A way.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/ufraterliber.showPublicProfile?language=EN>FraterLiber</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 202<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/29/02 2:34:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesmysteriouscreaturesfactorfiction.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What's Nessie?</span><hr size=1> If it's a real animal being spotted now and then, my bet is for some sort of really damned big sea slug or perhaps a slug or snail that is semi-aquatic.  Maybe it ventures into the water only to mate, and spends most of its time on land, in caves, or elsewhere.<br>
<br>
The report of the fellow who almost hit it with his car, if true, substantiates this idea.  Read his description.<br>
<br>
In any case, snails even have the right kind of head shape, and humps, and even better -- no bones.  They'd deliquesce upon death, and leave no trace.<br>
<br>
Now, granted, a snail even into the 20 - 30 feet range is huge, but it's not entirely unheard of, either.<br>
<br>
And keep in mind, this theory is entirely provisional upon IF Nessie is a real animal, of which I'm not convinced. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/utard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/2/02 1:15:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesmysteriouscreaturesfactorfiction.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~ab12885/tard.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What's Nessie?</span><hr size=1> Isn't that why we're in the "Folklore, Myths & Legends" forum?   <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesmysteriouscreaturesfactorfiction.showMessageRange?topicID=5.topic&start=1&stop=20>1</a> <b>2</b>  </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesmysteriouscreaturesfactorfiction.showPrevMessage?topicID=5.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesmysteriouscreaturesfactorfiction.showNextMessage?topicID=5.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesmysteriouscreaturesfactorfiction.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=31><img src=http://web.ukonline.co.uk/unexplained.m/images/addreply.jpeg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesmysteriouscreaturesfactorfiction.emailToFriend?topicID=5.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pu